{"title_page": "Animals Australia", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Animals Australia\n| logo   = Animals Australia logo.gif\n| type   = \n| founded_date      = 1980\n| founder           = [[Peter Singer]], [[Christine Townend]]\n| location          = [[Melbourne, Victoria]]\n| origins           =\n| key_people        = Glenys Oogjes, Lyn White\n| area_served       = [[Australia]]\n| product           =\n| mission           =\n| focus             = [[Animal welfare]]\n| method            = Investigations<br>Public awareness\n| revenue           =\n| endowment         =\n| num_volunteers    =\n| num_employees     =\n| num_members       =\n| subsid            =\n| owner             =\n| Non-profit_slogan =\n| homepage          = [http://www.animalsaustralia.org/ www.animalsaustralia.org]\n| dissolved         =\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n\n'''Animals Australia''' is an Australian animal protection organisation. Its aim is to investigate and expose [[cruelty to animals|animal cruelty]]. It is also a peak body representing over 40 [[animal rights]] groups around Australia.\n\nAnimals Australia is currently one of Animal Charity Evaluators Standout Charities.<ref name=updated>{{cite web |url=https://animalcharityevaluators.org/blog/updated-recommendations-december-2016/ |title=Updated Recommendations: December 2016 |first=Jon |last=Bockman |date=November 28, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAnimals Australia formed in 1980, originally as the Australian Federation of Animal Societies, founded by [[Peter Singer]] and [[Christine Townend]]. Animal protection groups in [[New Zealand]] were invited to join in 1986 and the organisation became the Australian and New Zealand Federation of Animal Societies. This formal Australian-New Zealand association ceased in 2005 and the federation now only uses the name \"Animals Australia\" - the name adopted as an Australian trading name in the late 1990s. Animals Australia representatives have contributed to Government enquiries and animal welfare law reform since the 1980s, and currently serve on State 'Animal Welfare Advisory Committees' and the Australian Animal Welfare Advisory Committee (AusAWAC).{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Campaigns ==\nAnimals Australia's goal is to \"significantly and permanently improve the welfare of all animals in Australia.\" {{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nAnimals Australia conducts investigations and public awareness campaigns on a range of animal welfare issues, including [[rodeos]], horse racing, the [[fur trade]], [[animal testing]], the dairy industry, fishing, flying fox conservation, kangaroo shooting, exotic animal circuses, sheared sheep, [[mulesing]], duck shooting, [[puppy farm]]s and [[greyhound racing]].<ref>[http://www.animalsaustralia.org/issues/ Animals Australia - \"The Issues\"]</ref> However they are most noted for their major work towards ending [[factory farming]],<ref>[http://www.makeitpossible.com Animals Australia - \"Make it Possible\"]</ref> the [[live export|live export trade]]<ref>[http://www.banliveexport.com Animals Australia - \"Ban Live Export\"]</ref> and most recently, [[greyhound racing]].<ref>http://www.greyhoundcruelty.com/ Animals Australia - \"Greyhound Racing Cruelty\"</ref>\n\nTheir subsidiary group for young animal advocates between the ages 13\u201326 is Animals Australia Unleashed.<ref>[http://www.unleashed.org.au/ Animals Australia - \"Unleashed\"]</ref>\n\nAnimals International is the global arm of Animals Australia.<ref>[http://www.animalsinternational.org/ Animals International]</ref> Established in 2014, Animals Australia campaigners have provided international colleague groups with evidence relating to cruelty in [[live export]]s; lobbied the [[World Organisation for Animal Health|OIE]] to improve animal welfare guidelines; worked with the [[Princess Alia bint Al Hussein|Princess Alia]] Foundation to improve slaughter practices in Jordan and contributed to creation of animal welfare legislation in [[Egypt]], [[Mauritius]] and [[Jordan]], amongst other projects.<ref>[http://banliveexport.com/features/working-worldwide-protect-animals.php Working Worldwide to Protect Animals from Cruelty - \"Ban Live Export\"]</ref>\n\n=== Live exports ===\n{{Main|Australian live export industry}}\n\nAnimals Australia's investigations in the Middle East in 2006 resulted in the first suspension of the [[Australian live animal export|live export]] trade and a benchmark prosecution of a live export company for cruelty.<ref name=\"Cases of Interest\">[http://www.bawp.org.au/cases-of-interest \"Emanuel Exports Magistrates Court Decision\"], Barristers Animal Welfare Panel, 14 February 2007</ref> Their investigations into the export of Australian cattle to Indonesia in 2011 led to a temporary suspension of the trade to Indonesia and the implementation of industry-wide Supply Chain Assurance Standards, monitored by the Australian [[Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry (Australia)|Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry]].<ref>[http://www.daff.gov.au/aqis/export/live-animals/livestock/escas Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry, Exporter Supply Chain Assurance System (ESCAS)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427063659/http://www.daff.gov.au/aqis/export/live-animals/livestock/escas |date=April 27, 2013 }}</ref> The Indonesian investigation led to an expos\u00e9 by [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC TV]]'s ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' program entitled \"A Bloody Business\"<ref>{{cite news| title = A Bloody Business| publisher = ABC| url = http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/content/2011/s3228880.htm| date = 2011-05-30| accessdate = 2013-06-13| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160504150136/http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/content/2011/s3228880.htm| archive-date = 2016-05-04| url-status = dead}}</ref> which earned the reporters a [[Gold Walkley|Gold Walkley Award]] and [[Logie Award|Logie]] for 'Most Outstanding Public Affairs Report'.<ref>{{cite news| title = Four Corners wins Gold Walkley| publisher = ABC| url = http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/stories/2011/11/29/3378946.htm| date = 2011-11-29| accessdate = 2013-06-13| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140224132557/http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/stories/2011/11/29/3378946.htm| archive-date = 2014-02-24| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Factory farming ===\nIn October 2012 Animals Australia launched its largest ever public awareness campaign initiative called \"Make it Possible\", with the goal of ending factory farming in Australia.<ref>[http://www.campaignbrief.com/2012/10/animal-australia-launches-make.html Campaign Brief - Animals Australia launches 'Make it Possible' public awareness campaign via LOUD]</ref> A series of advertisements, featuring animated pigs and chickens and a musical soundtrack to the song [[Somewhere (song)|Somewhere]], performed by players from the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]], was played on commercial television stations and in cinemas. The two-minute film received the 2012 Mobius Award for excellence in advertising for the cinema/in-flight category.<ref>[http://www.mobiusawards.com/awards/index.asp?PROCESS=Y&F_ENTRY_YEAR=2012&F_TITLE01=&F_AWARD=&F_CATEGORY01=&F_MEDIUM=CINEMA+%2F+IN-FLIGHT&F_KEYWORDS=&F_MATCH_TYPE=OR&submit1=Submit Mobius Awards - 2012 Winners] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806155028/http://www.mobiusawards.com/awards/index.asp?PROCESS=Y&F_ENTRY_YEAR=2012&F_TITLE01=&F_AWARD=&F_CATEGORY01=&F_MEDIUM=CINEMA+%2F+IN-FLIGHT&F_KEYWORDS=&F_MATCH_TYPE=OR&submit1=Submit |date=August 6, 2013 }}</ref> The film was accompanied by celebrity endorsements, such as from [[Michael Caton]], [[Missy Higgins]], [[Dave Hughes]], [[Michelle Bridges]], [[Rove McManus]] and others.<ref>[http://www.makeitpossible.com/ambassadors/ Make it Possible Ambassadors]</ref> In response to the Make it Possible campaign, [[Coles Supermarkets|Coles]] supermarkets announced a fast-tracked phase out of [[battery cage]] eggs and pork products produced with the use of [[sow stall]]s for their home brand products by January 2013.<ref>{{cite news| title = Coles Tackles Factory Farming | publisher = The Age | url = http://www.smh.com.au/national/coles-tackles-factory-farming-20121022-281gt.html | date =2012-10-23|accessdate = 2013-06-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Greyhound racing ===\nFollowing joint investigations with [[Animal Liberation Queensland]], in February 2015 Animals Australia exposed 'live baiting'<ref>{{cite news |title=Greyhound Cruelty |publisher=Animals Australia |url=http://www.greyhoundcruelty.com }}</ref> training methods in the greyhound industry, reigniting the campaign to end greyhound racing. The campaign reveals some top figures within greyhound racing using live possums, rabbits and piglets as 'bait' to train their greyhounds. It also focuses on the widespread abuse of greyhounds in the industry, including the killing of thousands of young and healthy dogs every year.{{citation needed|date= July 2016}}\n\nIn December 2015, Animals Australia exposed the export of Australian greyhounds to China and Macau.<ref name=abc-greyh-macau/> At the Canidrome racetrack in Macau life-threatening injuries are a daily occurrence, and no Australian greyhound is on record as surviving for longer than 3 years.{{citation needed|date= July 2016}} Canidrome has a 100% euthanasia rate of Australian greyhounds.<ref>{{cite news|title='Slow' Australian greyhounds being exported to Macau, China to go on 'death row' |publisher=ABC |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-09/greyhounds-exported-to-macau-china-against-industry-rules/7014434 |date=2015-12-09}}</ref>\n\nThe Vietnamese greyhound racing industry, where investigation footage reveals unwanted dogs being injected with an insecticide and dying in agony, was set up by Australian industry interests.<ref name=abc-greyh-macau>{{cite news |title=Australian greyhounds deemed too slow exported to Macau, China against industry rules |publisher=ABC |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2015/s4369266.htm |date=2015-12-09}}</ref>\n\n== People ==\n\n=== Glenys Oogjes - Executive Director ===\nGlenys Oogjes is one of Australia's longest serving animal advocates. She was raised on a Victorian dairy farm and has a degree in Behavioural Science. She has contributed to many national reviews of Codes of Practice and animal welfare laws in each Australian State and Territory. Oogjes has also worked to achieve greater protection for animals through representation on various committees including the Victorian Animal Welfare Advisory Committee, Institutional Animal Ethics committees, and on the Advisory Committee of the Animal Welfare Science Centre.<ref>[http://www.australiananimalwelfare.com.au/content/glenys-oogjes Australian Animal Welfare Strategy Advisory Committee - Glenys Oogjes] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421140204/http://www.australiananimalwelfare.com.au/content/glenys-oogjes |date=April 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOogjes was one of the instigators of the Australian Animal Welfare Strategy<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.australiananimalwelfare.com.au/ |title=Australian Animal Welfare Strategy |access-date=2013-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520151414/http://australiananimalwelfare.com.au/ |archive-date=2013-05-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  and represents animal advocacy groups on the Australian Animal Welfare Advisory Committee<ref>[http://www.daff.gov.au/animal-plant-health/welfare/aaws/committee Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry - Australian Animal Welfare Strategy Advisory Committee (AusAWAC)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525141824/http://www.daff.gov.au/animal-plant-health/welfare/aaws/committee |date=May 25, 2013 }}</ref>  which provides animal welfare advice to the Federal and State Australian Agriculture Ministers.\n\n=== Lyn White AM - Campaign Director and Investigator ===\nFormerly a South Australian police officer, White served as Australian Director of the [[Animals Asia Foundation]] on [[Southeast Asia]] animal cruelty issues before joining Animals Australia in 2003.<ref>{{cite news| title = The Liberator | publisher = ABC - Australian Story | url = http://www.abc.net.au/austory/transcripts/s549909.htm | date =2002-05-13}}</ref>  Since 2003, White has conducted numerous investigations in the Middle East and Indonesia into the treatment of live exported animals from Australia.<ref>[http://banliveexport.com/investigations/ Ban Live Export - Investigations]</ref>\n\nEvidence gathered has resulted in a leading live export company being prosecuted for animal cruelty and three 60 Minutes<ref>{{cite news| title = A Cruel Trade | publisher = Nine Network - 60 Minutes| url = http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/stories/richardcarleton/259366/a-cruel-trade | date =February 26, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Ship of Shame | publisher = Nine Network - 60 Minutes| url = http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/article/259096/ship-of-shame | date =September 21, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Making a Killing | publisher = Nine Network - 60 Minutes| url = http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/article/259069/making-a-killing | date =July 27, 2003}}</ref>  and three 7.30 Report segments<ref>{{cite news| title = Animal cruelty throws spotlight on live sheep trade | publisher = ABC - 7:30 Report | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-12-02/animal-cruelty-throws-spotlight-on-live-sheep-trade/2671652 | date =December 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Dramatic evidence of cruelty in the live sheep trade | publisher = ABC - 7:30 Report | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2007-10-11/dramatic-evidence-of-cruelty-in-the-live-sheep/2678806 | date =September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Live cattle exports under fire again | publisher = ABC - 7:30 Report | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-08-24/live-cattle-exports-under-fire-again/2854394 | date =August 24, 2011}}</ref> highlighting brutal treatment of exported Australian animals. White 's January 2006 investigation in Egypt resulted in the Australian Federal Government suspending the live cattle trade to Egypt.<ref>{{cite news| title = Live Exports to Egypt Suspended | publisher = Chris Johnson - Sydney Morning Herald | url = http://www.smh.com.au/environment/animals/live-exports-to-egypt-suspended-20130504-2izb0.html | date =May 4, 2013}}</ref>  In Jordan, White has assisted H.R.H. [[Princess Alia bint Al Hussein]] to achieve animal welfare breakthroughs in the country and acts as Chief Advisor to the Princess Alia Foundation.<ref>{{cite news| title = Animal Instincts | publisher = Liza Power - The Age | url = http://www.theage.com.au/national/melbourne-life/animal-instincts-20101201-18gnv.html | date =December 2, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, footage obtained by White and a co-investigator in 11 Indonesian slaughterhouses processing Australian cattle was featured on ABC's Four Corners program.<ref>{{cite news| title = A Bloody Business | publisher = ABC - Four Corners | url = http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/special_eds/20110530/cattle/ | date =May 30, 2011}}</ref> The resulting story led to the suspension of live exports to Indonesia and unprecedented public and political pressure to end the trade.\n\nWhite was a state finalist for the 2012 [[Australian of the Year]] awards,<ref>{{cite news| title = White in Australian of the Year Running | publisher = Sarah Scopelianos - The Weekly Times Now | url = http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2011/11/03/402671_latest-news.html | date =November 3, 2011}}</ref> and was named 2nd in a list of Melbourne's 100 most influential people of 2011 by The Age Melbourne Magazine.<ref>{{cite news| title = From a lifesaver to a judge and 98 in between, Melbourne's most notable | publisher = Angus Holland - The Age Melbourne Magazine| url = http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/from-a-lifesaver-to-a-judge-and-98-in-between-melbournes-most-notable-20111207-1oj8f.html | date =December 8, 2011}}</ref> She was made a Member of the [[Order of Australia]] (AM) in the 2014 [[Queen's Birthday Honours]] for \"significant service to the community as an animal rights and welfare advocate\".<ref>[http://www.gg.gov.au/queens-birthday-2014-honours-list Governor-General of the Commonwealth of Australia - \"The Queen's Birthday 2014 Honours List\"]</ref> She has been described by bioethicist and author of [[Animal Liberation (book)|Animal Liberation]], [[Peter Singer]], as the most effective animal campaigner of his generation.<ref>{{cite news | title = The Razor's Edge | publisher = ABC - Australian Story | url = http://www.abc.net.au/austory/content/2012/s3487219.htm | date = April 23, 2012 | access-date = June 14, 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160910194859/http://www.abc.net.au/austory/content/2012/s3487219.htm | archive-date = September 10, 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n== Animal Charity Evaluators review ==\nAnimals Australia has been one of Animal Charity Evaluators' (ACE) Standout Charities in its annual recommendations since December 2015.<ref name=ace-review>{{cite web |url=https://animalcharityevaluators.org/research/charity-review/animals-australia/ |title=Animals Australia |accessdate=January 18, 2019 |author=Animal Charity Evaluators}}</ref>  ACE designates as Standout Charities those organizations which they do not feel are as strong as their Top Charities, but which excel in at least one way and are exceptionally strong compared to animal charities in general.<ref name=smith>{{cite web |url=http://animalcharityevaluators.org/blog/our-thinking-on-standout-organizations/ |title=Our Thinking on Standout Organizations |first=Allison |last=Smith |date=June 9, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn its December 2015 review of Animals Australia, ACE cites Animals Australia's strengths as their \"ability to steer public conversation in Australia in a more animal friendly direction\", concrete successes such as getting McDonald's to phase out [[battery cage|battery eggs]], a self-critical mindset, and significant growth in recent years.  Their weaknesses, according to ACE, include significant spending to help much smaller populations of animals (e.g. those used in live export or puppy farming, as opposed to animal agriculture), and the fact that its activities are largely confined to Australia.<ref name=ace-review />\n\nNote in the latest review (November 2018) Animals Australia declined to be reviewed stating that they were to busy.<ref name=\"ace-review\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Animal welfare and rights in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.animalsaustralia.org Animals Australia Official Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3RcYC2_7Ias6mO39k1LVLQ Animals Australia -YouTube channel]\n* [http://www.animalsinternational.org Animals International]\n* [http://www.banliveexport.com Ban Live Export]\n* [http://www.makeitpossible.com Make it Possible]\n* [http://www.unleashed.org.au Animals Australia Unleashed]\n* [http://www.greyhoundcruelty.com/ Greyhound Racing Cruelty]\n\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare organisations based in Australia]]\n[[Category:Animal charities based in Australia]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in Victoria (Australia)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name   = Animals Australia\n| logo   = Animals Australia logo.gif\n| type   = \n| founded_date      = 1980\n| founder           = [[Peter Singer]], [[Christine Townend]]\n| location          = [[Melbourne, Victoria]]\n| origins           =\n| key_people        = Glenys Oogjes, Lyn White\n| area_served       = [[Australia]]\n| product           =\n| mission           =\n| focus             = [[Animal welfare]]\n| method            = Investigations<br>Public awareness\n| revenue           =\n| endowment         =\n| num_volunteers    =\n| num_employees     =\n| num_members       =\n| subsid            =\n| owner             =\n| Non-profit_slogan =\n| homepage          = [http://www.animalsaustralia.org/ www.animalsaustralia.org]\n| dissolved         =\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n\n'''Animals Australia''' is an Australian animal protection organisation. Its aim is to investigate and expose [[cruelty to animals|animal cruelty]]. It is also a peak body representing over 40 [[animal rights]] groups around Australia.\n\nAnimals Australia is currently one of Animal Charity Evaluators Standout Charities.<ref name=updated>{{cite web |url=https://animalcharityevaluators.org/blog/updated-recommendations-december-2016/ |title=Updated Recommendations: December 2016 |first=Jon |last=Bockman |date=November 28, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAnimals Australia formed in 1980, originally as the Australian Federation of Animal Societies, founded by [[Peter Singer]] and [[Christine Townend]]. Animal protection groups in [[New Zealand]] were invited to join in 1986 and the organisation became the Australian and New Zealand Federation of Animal Societies. This formal Australian-New Zealand association ceased in 2005 and the federation now only uses the name \"Animals Australia\" - the name adopted as an Australian trading name in the late 1990's. Animals Australia representatives have contributed to Government enquiries and animal welfare law reform since the 1980's, and currently serve on State 'Animal Welfare Advisory Committees' and the Australian Animal Welfare Advisory Committee (AusAWAC).{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Campaigns ==\nAnimals Australia's goal is to \"significantly and permanently improve the welfare of all animals in Australia.\" {{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nAnimals Australia conducts investigations and public awareness campaigns on a range of animal welfare issues, including [[rodeos]], horse racing, the [[fur trade]], [[animal testing]], the dairy industry, fishing, flying fox conservation, kangaroo shooting, exotic animal circuses, sheared sheep, [[mulesing]], duck shooting, [[puppy farm]]s and [[greyhound racing]].<ref>[http://www.animalsaustralia.org/issues/ Animals Australia - \"The Issues\"]</ref> However they are most noted for their major work towards ending [[factory farming]],<ref>[http://www.makeitpossible.com Animals Australia - \"Make it Possible\"]</ref> the [[live export|live export trade]]<ref>[http://www.banliveexport.com Animals Australia - \"Ban Live Export\"]</ref> and most recently, [[greyhound racing]].<ref>http://www.greyhoundcruelty.com/ Animals Australia - \"Greyhound Racing Cruelty\"</ref>\n\nTheir subsidiary group for young animal advocates between the ages 13\u201326 is Animals Australia Unleashed.<ref>[http://www.unleashed.org.au/ Animals Australia - \"Unleashed\"]</ref>\n\nAnimals International is the global arm of Animals Australia.<ref>[http://www.animalsinternational.org/ Animals International]</ref> Established in 2014, Animals Australia campaigners have provided international colleague groups with evidence relating to cruelty in [[live export]]s; lobbied the [[World Organisation for Animal Health|OIE]] to improve animal welfare guidelines; worked with the [[Princess Alia bint Al Hussein|Princess Alia]] Foundation to improve slaughter practices in Jordan and contributed to creation of animal welfare legislation in [[Egypt]], [[Mauritius]] and [[Jordan]], amongst other projects.<ref>[http://banliveexport.com/features/working-worldwide-protect-animals.php Working Worldwide to Protect Animals from Cruelty - \"Ban Live Export\"]</ref>\n\n=== Live exports ===\n{{Main|Australian live export industry}}\n\nAnimals Australia's investigations in the Middle East in 2006 resulted in the first suspension of the [[Australian live animal export|live export]] trade and a benchmark prosecution of a live export company for cruelty.<ref name=\"Cases of Interest\">[http://www.bawp.org.au/cases-of-interest \"Emanuel Exports Magistrates Court Decision\"], Barristers Animal Welfare Panel, 14 February 2007</ref> Their investigations into the export of Australian cattle to Indonesia in 2011 led to a temporary suspension of the trade to Indonesia and the implementation of industry-wide Supply Chain Assurance Standards, monitored by the Australian [[Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry (Australia)|Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry]].<ref>[http://www.daff.gov.au/aqis/export/live-animals/livestock/escas Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry, Exporter Supply Chain Assurance System (ESCAS)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427063659/http://www.daff.gov.au/aqis/export/live-animals/livestock/escas |date=April 27, 2013 }}</ref> The Indonesian investigation led to an expos\u00e9 by [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC TV]]'s ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' program entitled \"A Bloody Business\"<ref>{{cite news| title = A Bloody Business| publisher = ABC| url = http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/content/2011/s3228880.htm| date = 2011-05-30| accessdate = 2013-06-13| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160504150136/http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/content/2011/s3228880.htm| archive-date = 2016-05-04| url-status = dead}}</ref> which earned the reporters a [[Gold Walkley|Gold Walkley Award]] and [[Logie Award|Logie]] for 'Most Outstanding Public Affairs Report'.<ref>{{cite news| title = Four Corners wins Gold Walkley| publisher = ABC| url = http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/stories/2011/11/29/3378946.htm| date = 2011-11-29| accessdate = 2013-06-13| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140224132557/http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/stories/2011/11/29/3378946.htm| archive-date = 2014-02-24| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Factory farming ===\nIn October 2012 Animals Australia launched its largest ever public awareness campaign initiative called \"Make it Possible\", with the goal of ending factory farming in Australia.<ref>[http://www.campaignbrief.com/2012/10/animal-australia-launches-make.html Campaign Brief - Animals Australia launches 'Make it Possible' public awareness campaign via LOUD]</ref> A series of advertisements, featuring animated pigs and chickens and a musical soundtrack to the song [[Somewhere (song)|Somewhere]], performed by players from the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]], was played on commercial television stations and in cinemas. The two-minute film received the 2012 Mobius Award for excellence in advertising for the cinema/in-flight category.<ref>[http://www.mobiusawards.com/awards/index.asp?PROCESS=Y&F_ENTRY_YEAR=2012&F_TITLE01=&F_AWARD=&F_CATEGORY01=&F_MEDIUM=CINEMA+%2F+IN-FLIGHT&F_KEYWORDS=&F_MATCH_TYPE=OR&submit1=Submit Mobius Awards - 2012 Winners] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806155028/http://www.mobiusawards.com/awards/index.asp?PROCESS=Y&F_ENTRY_YEAR=2012&F_TITLE01=&F_AWARD=&F_CATEGORY01=&F_MEDIUM=CINEMA+%2F+IN-FLIGHT&F_KEYWORDS=&F_MATCH_TYPE=OR&submit1=Submit |date=August 6, 2013 }}</ref> The film was accompanied by celebrity endorsements, such as from [[Michael Caton]], [[Missy Higgins]], [[Dave Hughes]], [[Michelle Bridges]], [[Rove McManus]] and others.<ref>[http://www.makeitpossible.com/ambassadors/ Make it Possible Ambassadors]</ref> In response to the Make it Possible campaign, [[Coles Supermarkets|Coles]] supermarkets announced a fast-tracked phase out of [[battery cage]] eggs and pork products produced with the use of [[sow stall]]s for their home brand products by January 2013.<ref>{{cite news| title = Coles Tackles Factory Farming | publisher = The Age | url = http://www.smh.com.au/national/coles-tackles-factory-farming-20121022-281gt.html | date =2012-10-23|accessdate = 2013-06-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Greyhound racing ===\nFollowing joint investigations with [[Animal Liberation Queensland]], in February 2015 Animals Australia exposed 'live baiting'<ref>{{cite news |title=Greyhound Cruelty |publisher=Animals Australia |url=http://www.greyhoundcruelty.com }}</ref> training methods in the greyhound industry, reigniting the campaign to end greyhound racing. The campaign reveals some top figures within greyhound racing using live possums, rabbits and piglets as 'bait' to train their greyhounds. It also focuses on the widespread abuse of greyhounds in the industry, including the killing of thousands of young and healthy dogs every year.{{citation needed|date= July 2016}}\n\nIn December 2015, Animals Australia exposed the export of Australian greyhounds to China and Macau.<ref name=abc-greyh-macau/> At the Canidrome racetrack in Macau life-threatening injuries are a daily occurrence, and no Australian greyhound is on record as surviving for longer than 3 years.{{citation needed|date= July 2016}} Canidrome has a 100% euthanasia rate of Australian greyhounds.<ref>{{cite news|title='Slow' Australian greyhounds being exported to Macau, China to go on 'death row' |publisher=ABC |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-09/greyhounds-exported-to-macau-china-against-industry-rules/7014434 |date=2015-12-09}}</ref>\n\nThe Vietnamese greyhound racing industry, where investigation footage reveals unwanted dogs being injected with an insecticide and dying in agony, was set up by Australian industry interests.<ref name=abc-greyh-macau>{{cite news |title=Australian greyhounds deemed too slow exported to Macau, China against industry rules |publisher=ABC |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2015/s4369266.htm |date=2015-12-09}}</ref>\n\n== People ==\n\n=== Glenys Oogjes - Executive Director ===\nGlenys Oogjes is one of Australia's longest serving animal advocates. She was raised on a Victorian dairy farm and has a degree in Behavioural Science. She has contributed to many national reviews of Codes of Practice and animal welfare laws in each Australian State and Territory. Oogjes has also worked to achieve greater protection for animals through representation on various committees including the Victorian Animal Welfare Advisory Committee, Institutional Animal Ethics committees, and on the Advisory Committee of the Animal Welfare Science Centre.<ref>[http://www.australiananimalwelfare.com.au/content/glenys-oogjes Australian Animal Welfare Strategy Advisory Committee - Glenys Oogjes] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421140204/http://www.australiananimalwelfare.com.au/content/glenys-oogjes |date=April 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOogjes was one of the instigators of the Australian Animal Welfare Strategy<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.australiananimalwelfare.com.au/ |title=Australian Animal Welfare Strategy |access-date=2013-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520151414/http://australiananimalwelfare.com.au/ |archive-date=2013-05-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  and represents animal advocacy groups on the Australian Animal Welfare Advisory Committee<ref>[http://www.daff.gov.au/animal-plant-health/welfare/aaws/committee Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry - Australian Animal Welfare Strategy Advisory Committee (AusAWAC)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525141824/http://www.daff.gov.au/animal-plant-health/welfare/aaws/committee |date=May 25, 2013 }}</ref>  which provides animal welfare advice to the Federal and State Australian Agriculture Ministers.\n\n=== Lyn White AM - Campaign Director and Investigator ===\nFormerly a South Australian police officer, White served as Australian Director of the [[Animals Asia Foundation]] on [[Southeast Asia]] animal cruelty issues before joining Animals Australia in 2003.<ref>{{cite news| title = The Liberator | publisher = ABC - Australian Story | url = http://www.abc.net.au/austory/transcripts/s549909.htm | date =2002-05-13}}</ref>  Since 2003, White has conducted numerous investigations in the Middle East and Indonesia into the treatment of live exported animals from Australia.<ref>[http://banliveexport.com/investigations/ Ban Live Export - Investigations]</ref>\n\nEvidence gathered has resulted in a leading live export company being prosecuted for animal cruelty and three 60 Minutes<ref>{{cite news| title = A Cruel Trade | publisher = Nine Network - 60 Minutes| url = http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/stories/richardcarleton/259366/a-cruel-trade | date =February 26, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Ship of Shame | publisher = Nine Network - 60 Minutes| url = http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/article/259096/ship-of-shame | date =September 21, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Making a Killing | publisher = Nine Network - 60 Minutes| url = http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/article/259069/making-a-killing | date =July 27, 2003}}</ref>  and three 7.30 Report segments<ref>{{cite news| title = Animal cruelty throws spotlight on live sheep trade | publisher = ABC - 7:30 Report | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-12-02/animal-cruelty-throws-spotlight-on-live-sheep-trade/2671652 | date =December 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Dramatic evidence of cruelty in the live sheep trade | publisher = ABC - 7:30 Report | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2007-10-11/dramatic-evidence-of-cruelty-in-the-live-sheep/2678806 | date =September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Live cattle exports under fire again | publisher = ABC - 7:30 Report | url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-08-24/live-cattle-exports-under-fire-again/2854394 | date =August 24, 2011}}</ref> highlighting brutal treatment of exported Australian animals. White 's January 2006 investigation in Egypt resulted in the Australian Federal Government suspending the live cattle trade to Egypt.<ref>{{cite news| title = Live Exports to Egypt Suspended | publisher = Chris Johnson - Sydney Morning Herald | url = http://www.smh.com.au/environment/animals/live-exports-to-egypt-suspended-20130504-2izb0.html | date =May 4, 2013}}</ref>  In Jordan, White has assisted H.R.H. [[Princess Alia bint Al Hussein]] to achieve animal welfare breakthroughs in the country and acts as Chief Advisor to the Princess Alia Foundation.<ref>{{cite news| title = Animal Instincts | publisher = Liza Power - The Age | url = http://www.theage.com.au/national/melbourne-life/animal-instincts-20101201-18gnv.html | date =December 2, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, footage obtained by White and a co-investigator in 11 Indonesian slaughterhouses processing Australian cattle was featured on ABC's Four Corners program.<ref>{{cite news| title = A Bloody Business | publisher = ABC - Four Corners | url = http://www.abc.net.au/4corners/special_eds/20110530/cattle/ | date =May 30, 2011}}</ref> The resulting story led to the suspension of live exports to Indonesia and unprecedented public and political pressure to end the trade.\n\nWhite was a state finalist for the 2012 [[Australian of the Year]] awards,<ref>{{cite news| title = White in Australian of the Year Running | publisher = Sarah Scopelianos - The Weekly Times Now | url = http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2011/11/03/402671_latest-news.html | date =November 3, 2011}}</ref> and was named 2nd in a list of Melbourne's 100 most influential people of 2011 by The Age Melbourne Magazine.<ref>{{cite news| title = From a lifesaver to a judge and 98 in between, Melbourne's most notable | publisher = Angus Holland - The Age Melbourne Magazine| url = http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/from-a-lifesaver-to-a-judge-and-98-in-between-melbournes-most-notable-20111207-1oj8f.html | date =December 8, 2011}}</ref> She was made a Member of the [[Order of Australia]] (AM) in the 2014 [[Queen's Birthday Honours]] for \"significant service to the community as an animal rights and welfare advocate\".<ref>[http://www.gg.gov.au/queens-birthday-2014-honours-list Governor-General of the Commonwealth of Australia - \"The Queen's Birthday 2014 Honours List\"]</ref> She has been described by bioethicist and author of [[Animal Liberation (book)|Animal Liberation]], [[Peter Singer]], as the most effective animal campaigner of his generation.<ref>{{cite news | title = The Razor's Edge | publisher = ABC - Australian Story | url = http://www.abc.net.au/austory/content/2012/s3487219.htm | date = April 23, 2012 | access-date = June 14, 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160910194859/http://www.abc.net.au/austory/content/2012/s3487219.htm | archive-date = September 10, 2016 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n== Animal Charity Evaluators review ==\nAnimals Australia has been one of Animal Charity Evaluators' (ACE) Standout Charities in its annual recommendations since December 2015.<ref name=ace-review>{{cite web |url=https://animalcharityevaluators.org/research/charity-review/animals-australia/ |title=Animals Australia |accessdate=January 18, 2019 |author=Animal Charity Evaluators}}</ref>  ACE designates as Standout Charities those organizations which they do not feel are as strong as their Top Charities, but which excel in at least one way and are exceptionally strong compared to animal charities in general.<ref name=smith>{{cite web |url=http://animalcharityevaluators.org/blog/our-thinking-on-standout-organizations/ |title=Our Thinking on Standout Organizations |first=Allison |last=Smith |date=June 9, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn its December 2015 review of Animals Australia, ACE cites Animals Australia's strengths as their \"ability to steer public conversation in Australia in a more animal friendly direction\", concrete successes such as getting McDonald's to phase out [[battery cage|battery eggs]], a self-critical mindset, and significant growth in recent years.  Their weaknesses, according to ACE, include significant spending to help much smaller populations of animals (e.g. those used in live export or puppy farming, as opposed to animal agriculture), and the fact that its activities are largely confined to Australia.<ref name=ace-review />\n\nNote in the latest review (November 2018) Animals Australia declined to be reviewed stating that they were to busy.<ref name=\"ace-review\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Animal welfare and rights in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.animalsaustralia.org Animals Australia Official Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3RcYC2_7Ias6mO39k1LVLQ Animals Australia -YouTube channel]\n* [http://www.animalsinternational.org Animals International]\n* [http://www.banliveexport.com Ban Live Export]\n* [http://www.makeitpossible.com Make it Possible]\n* [http://www.unleashed.org.au Animals Australia Unleashed]\n* [http://www.greyhoundcruelty.com/ Greyhound Racing Cruelty]\n\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare organisations based in Australia]]\n[[Category:Animal charities based in Australia]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in Victoria (Australia)]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animals_Australia"}
